observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the LCE 

(a) require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer as General Services Officer to 

(i) maintain property ledger cards and PPE ledger cards to substantiate the existence, completeness and reliability of items composing the respective PPE accounts; 

(ii) facilitate the reconciliation process for identification of any discrepancies in PPE records; and 

(iii) work on the completion of physical inventory taking and prepare the Report of Physical Count of PPE; 

(b) designate a property officer to discharge the property management custodial functions of the Municipality; 

(c) require the Municipal Accountant to submit all the unsubmitted disbursement vouchers with transaction value of ₱2,404,156.74 for the payment to contractors and suppliers for the procured PPE and infrastructure projects; 

(d) submit the lacking documentary requirements to support the payment on the procured parcel of land costing ₱4,685,448.00; and 

(e) submit justification on the necessity of the procurement of 13 units of Apple iPads to preclude the transaction from being disallowed in audit.

We recommended that the LCE require compliance with the provisions of RA No. 9184 by directing the Bids and Awards Committee/BAC Secretariat to 

(i)  attach proof of invitation of three observers in writing in all stages of procurement and;  

(ii) post the advertisement, notices of award and approved contract at the PHILGEPS and at prescribed places.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) 

(a) require the Municipal Accounting Office to

(i) make the necessary accounting entries to book up the unrecognized PPE in the books; 

(ii) review the Trust Fund books to identify the purchased PPE in previous years that were not recognized in the books; 

(iii) be assertive in obtaining information related to donated/transferred PPE to the Municipality to ensure their timely recognition in the books; and 

(iv) provide depreciation for all depreciable assets; and 

(b) fully utilize the GSO unit by consolidating all property management related tasks under its turf including but not limited to the 

(i) exertion of efforts to gather the necessary documents for titling of lots under the name of the Municipality; 

(ii) establishment and maintenance of property cards for each class of PPE; 

(iii) completion of physical inventory taking; 

(iv) preparation of the Report of Physical Count of PPE; 

(v) safekeeping and custody of property documents; and

(vi) promulgation of policies to achieve sufficient sound property management practices within the agency.

We reiterated our recommendation that Management require the officials concerned to: 

(a) speed up the preparation of documents necessary for the registration of the lots in the Municipality’s name with the Registry of Deeds; 




(b) exert best efforts to make the necessary research for the retrieval of documents supporting the untitled parcels of land including the basis for the valuation of the lots; 


(c) prioritize the completion of inventory taking and submit the RPCPPE; 



(d) establish and maintain updated PPELCs and PCs for reconciliation of accounting and property records.

